Cross-Domain Transfer (your version, refined)

“A pattern learned in one domain—often under pressure—is abstracted and successfully applied in a different domain with a similar structure.”

In your bird chain:

* Domain A: small birds → crow (harassment/mobbing)
* Domain B: crow → hawk (same tactic, new opponent)

The crow isn’t copying the bird
It’s copying the structure of the interaction:

* angle of approach
* persistence
* timing windows
* risk vs reward

⸻

What makes this high-power transfer

Most people fail at cross-domain transfer because they copy surface features.

You’re pointing at copying invariants.

Surface (low power)

* “Small birds chase bigger birds → I’ll do that”

Structural (high power)

* “Repeated, coordinated harassment from safe angles overwhelms a stronger opponent”

That second one transfers anywhere.

⸻

The 3-layer model (clean and reusable)

1) Experience (pressure layer)
You encounter something that works on you

2) Abstraction (invariant layer)
You strip it down to what actually made it work

3) Redeployment (transfer layer)
You apply it in a different domain with similar constraints

⸻

Why it works so well

* Reality-tested → it already beat something real
* Embodied → you felt it, not just read it
* Generalizable → structure survives translation

And most importantly:

The system doesn’t care about domain labels—only structure.

